Hello! I'm Javier and im a Data Science Master's Degree student. I have made a library to automate the processes in which data scientists invest most part of the time. The library is divided into three sections: EDA, feature engineering and feature selection.¶

Give me a like if you found it useful and leave me a comment if you have any suggestion!¶






In [3]:
import pandas as pd
import arcticdata.ExploratoryDataAnalysis as eda

import os
for dirname, _, filenames in os.walk('/kaggle/input'):
    for filename in filenames:
        print(os.path.join(dirname, filename))

/kaggle/input/titanic/gender_submission.csv

Before starting with the dataset, the library counts with a project checklist if you are lost in any moment and you don't remember what you need to do (This checklist is based in Aurélien Géron book called "Hands-On Machine Learning with Scikit-Learn, Keras & Tensorflow")¶

In [4]:
eda.project_checklist()

Frame the problem
	-Define the objective
	-Supervised/Unsupervised, online/offline
	-Measure of the performance
	-Minimum performance needed to reach the objective
	-Assumptions

Get the data
	-Document where is the data
	-Check how much space it takes
	-Check legal obligations and get authorization
	-Create a workspace
	-Convert the data to a good format
	-Delete or protect sensitive information
	-Check the type of data
	-Put a test set aside

Explore the data
	-Create a copy of the data for exploration
	-Study each attribute
	-Identify the target attribute if supervised learning
	-Visualize the data
	-Study the correlations
	-Identify the transformations you need
	-Document what you have learned

Prepare the data
	-Work on copies of the data
	-Write functions for all transformations
	-Data cleaning (outliers and missing values)
	-Feature selection (Drop attributes with no useful information)
	-Feature engineering (Discretize, Decompose, etc)
	-Feature scaling (standardize, normalize)

Shortlist promising models
	-Automate this steps as much as posible
	-Train many quick-and-dirty models using standar parameters
	-Measure and compare the performance with N-fold CV and compute the mean and sd of the performances
	-Analyze the most significant variables for each algorithm
	-Analyze the type of errors the models make
	-Shortlist the top promising models

Fine-Tune the system
	-Fine-Tune hyperparameters using CV
	-Random Search > Grid Search unless very few hyperparameters to explore
	-If training is very long, use Bayesian optimization approach
	-Use ensemble methods for better performance
	-Measure model performance on the test set to get the generalization error

Present your solution
	-Document what you have done
	-Create a nice presentation
	-Explain why the solution archieves the objective
	-Present interesting points and key findings
Launch
	-Get the solution ready to production
	-Write monitoring code and trigger alerts
